  "prompt": "Is there a 5 star general?",
  "response": "Yes, the rank of **Five-Star General** (officially known as **General of the Army**) is the highest possible rank in the United States military. It ranks above a four-star general and is equivalent to the rank of **Fleet Admiral** in the U.S. Navy. The rank was created during World War II to ensure that U.S. military leaders had equivalent authority to their Allied counterparts.\n\n### Key Facts About Five-Star Generals:\n1. **History**: The rank was established in 1944.\n2. **Rarity**: Only nine individuals have ever held this rank, and none are currently active.\n3. **Notable Five-Star Generals**:\n   - **George C. Marshall** (Army)\n   - **Douglas MacArthur** (Army)\n   - **Dwight D. Eisenhower** (Army) (later became U.S. President)\n   - **Omar Bradley** (Army)\n4. **Retirement**: The rank was retired in 1981, and no new five-star generals have been appointed since.\n5. **Purpose**: The rank was primarily created for wartime leadership and to signify the highest level of military command.\n\nThe rank of Five-Star General is largely ceremonial today, as there has been no need to appoint one since World War II and the Korean War era.",
